# React context provider structure

When a screen or feature orchestrator grows large (~150+ lines), or is likely to (multiple data sources, shared UI state, prop drilling), extract a **provider module** instead of keeping everything in the route file.

## When to apply

- Screen has **3+ hooks**, **multiple `useEffect`s**, or **prop drilling** through section components.
- State is **scoped to one screen/feature** (not app-wide).
- You expect the screen to keep growing (notes + activity + editor + offline cache, etc.).

**App-wide** providers (auth, theme) use the same layout under `src/context/<name>/`. **Feature-scoped** providers live under `features/<screen>/context/<name>/`.

## Folder layout

```
context/<name>/
  index.ts         # barrel — re-exports public API (relative paths only)
  context.ts       # ContextValue type + React.createContext
  provider.tsx     # <Name>Provider component (state, effects, memoized value)
  use-<name>.ts    # use<Name>() hook with guard
```

References: `src/context/auth/`, `src/context/theme/`, `src/features/standup/context/standup/`.

## File responsibilities

| File           | Exports                         | Contains                                                                         |
| -------------- | ------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `context.ts`   | `FooContextValue`, `FooContext` | Types and context object only — no hooks                                         |
| `provider.tsx` | `FooProvider`                   | State, effects, callbacks, `useMemo` value                                       |
| `use-foo.ts`   | `useFoo`                        | `useContext` + "must be within provider" guard                                   |
| `index.ts`     | re-exports                      | `./relative` paths only — no `@/context/self` or `@/features/<same>/context/...` |

## Route / screen pattern

Keep `src/app/` routes thin — layout + provider wrapper only:

```tsx
export default function StandupScreen() {
  return (
    <>
      <Stack.Screen options={{ title: 'Generate standup' }} />
      <StandupProvider>
        <StandupScreenContent />
      </StandupProvider>
    </>
  );
}
```

Split UI into **section components** under `features/<name>/components/` that call `useFoo()` — no prop drilling.

## Rules

- **No monolithic `foo-provider.tsx`** once the provider exceeds ~100 lines — split into the layout above.
- **`context.ts` stays pure** — no side effects, no provider logic.
- **Memoize provider value** with `useMemo` to limit re-renders.
- **`index.ts` only at the context module** (`context/<name>/index.ts`). No `src/context/index.ts` root barrel.
- **Avoid self-alias imports** inside the same context module — provider files import siblings via relative paths.

## Example imports

```tsx
// App root
import { AuthProvider } from '@/context/auth';
import { AppThemeProvider, useAppColorScheme } from '@/context/theme';

// Feature route
import { StandupProvider } from '@/features/standup/context/standup';

// Section component in same feature
import { useStandup } from '../context/standup';

// Inside provider module
import { StandupContext } from './context';
```
